  "text": "Isolate RST-1 B. canariense from R. sphaerocarpa could only grow at pH 7, the optimal pH for rhizobial growth, while strain RST-2 Phylobacterium myrsinacearum was basic resistant, capable of growth up to pH 9 [CITATION_1] ). [CITATION_2] reported that B. retamae occurred only in soils with pH higher than 7.5, which suggests that this species could be better adapted to alkaline soils. However, [CITATION_3] have noticed that, highly alkaline soils of pH above 8.5 tended to be high in contents of sodium chloride, bicarbonate and borate which reduce nitrogen fixation.",
